args: Lord Caspar? Priestess Aurelia?\nMight I introduce to you my fiancée?
I am Princess Chelle, and I am most\npleased to make your acquaintances.
I have heard much about you, Princess—\nand I see the tales of your great beauty\nhave not been exaggerated.
Wedding a princess of the royal family\nwill surely help Raywall's prosperity\ngrow more and more, Lord Elua.

My thanks, Lord Caspar, though such
prosperity is thanks in no small part to
those from the Holy City of Grams—
yourself included.
I hope we might continue to enjoy a\nprosperous exchange in the years to come.

Let us permit the unfortunate business
between our two lands to be a thing of the
past, and join hands as close neighbors
and bosom friends in the coming years.
It would appear we've navigated the\nwaters successfully—for today at least.
And Lord Caspar appears to have returned\nto his quarters, so all seems well for now.\nWhat say you, Cat Sìth?
Hmm? Oh, sure, I guess it'll be fine.
Well that's not very reassuring!\nAnd you call yourself my pactwyrm.
Can you blame me? Observing that man's\nevery move is boring.
Of course it is. We're not doing this for the\nsake of your amusement.
The chill in your words is hardly necessary.
Forgive us, Cat Sìth. We'll be in your debt\nif you can only assist for a little while yet.
Mrow, I am not especially bothered.\nBut is it really true?
There is a faction in Raywall that would\nleap at the chance to see us at war with\nGrams once more.
So it seems. A-purr-ently they remain\nresentful of the previous engagement.

Yet said previous war was fought over ten
years ago, was it not? Surely you humans
do not live long enough to carry such
animosity for so long?
It's true, we do not live quite so long as\nyou dragons, but old grudges can survive\nmany years in our hearts.
There are many people who fought with\nGrams personally, and others who lost\nparents, siblings, and children to them.
The problem is that it was not just Raywall\nwho was at war—Grams was as well.
So then Grams has its own share\nof individuals who seek war?
Indeed, and Lord Caspar is the one\nholding that faction in check.
Were he to die, public sentiment in Grams\nwould shift toward war in an eyeblink.
The war faction has long hoped for such\nan incident, and I suspect they will not\npass up this opportunity.
We cannot let our eye on Lord Caspar\nwaiver, not even for an instant.

If the enemy is aware that we have set a
strong watch, it will make it harder for
them to meddle. We absolutely must
put a stop to the assassination.
No. We aim for Priestess Aurelia.
As its name suggests, the Holy City is a\nplace where the Ilian Church's influence\nis quite strong.

And that influence will reach a zenith—
far outstripping even high government
officials—with the murder of such an
important and beloved priestess.
Grams will not take to silence if the\nassassination is a success.
In other words, it will be war, just as\nwe desire.
Go and see this done. For the sake of our\ndream, failure will not be tolerated.
Worry not. With their guard this light,\nI would have to try to fail.
Elua is under the impression that we are\ntargeting Caspar, and he will be well-\nprotected indeed.
But that will make it far easier to twist\nthe knife on Aurelia while their attention\nis distracted.

Failing at this task when they've left the
door wide would be an insult to assassins
everywhere. I will send a report soon when
the deed is done.
(This is Aurelia's room...\nSeems like she's fast asleep.)
(I regret the thought of taking a woman's\nlife, but it is your birth in Grams that\nwrongs you, priestess—not I.)
Worry not! Priestess Aurelia has been\nmoved to location most secure.
You're the princess! B-but how did...?!
I presume you mean ＂How did we know\nthat you were actually going to target\nPriestess Aurelia＂?
Truthfully, it's far stranger why you thought\nwe WOULDN'T know.
With your objective of fomenting strife with\nGrams so plain, it was a simple matter\nto suss out your plans.
And now, I believe I'll have you explain\nwho it is that you work for.

You believe I would sell my comrades out?
Perhaps that is how it works among you
foul royals, but you'll find I'm made of
sterner stuff!
I'd warn you not to be arrogant enough to\nbelieve you can take me on your own.

My, but I wonder which of us is truly
the arrogant one. Perhaps it's time to
teach you some regret for having
besmirched the dragon bloodline!
Are you quite all right, Princess?
Ah, Lord Elua! Just in time.\nYou'll find our miscreant lying there.
Rest easy, I did not kill him;\nI merely gave him a little caress.
Fascinating! This is no mean cutpurse,\nyet you handled him like a child.
I suppose that's what it is to be pactbound\nto a dragon. You surprise me yet again.
Why, it is I who is surprised, Lord Eula!\nI never would have believed that you\nmight use Priestess Aurelia as bait.
Though we may bandy about titles for\nmy person like ＂lord＂ and ＂marquis,＂\nmy position here is actually rather weak.
I am discomfited to admit this, but even\nwithin this city, I find myself not knowing\nwho my true friends and enemies are.
To protect my territory, it sometimes\nbehooves me to adopt bolder measures.
Yet if you only wanted to protect Priestess\nAurelia, you had but to strengthen her\nguard as you did with Lord Caspar.
It is as you surmise, Princess Chelle:\nI would have been most chagrined had the\nwar faction given up its assassination.
Had they failed to act, I would have lost\na golden opportunity to learn who is\nmasterminding their efforts.
To that end, I felt there was little option\nother than to imperil the good priestess.
Do you judge me for it?
Heh heh... Eeeeee hee hee hee!
Judge you? What possible reason\ncould I have for such contempt?
Indeed, I was just thinking that things\nare likely to go quite well with you.
